## The temple that no single pharaoh could finish.

Most temples were built by one king to one plan. Karnak was different. For more than two thousand years — longer than the span from us back to the Romans — pharaoh after pharaoh added to it: a hall here, a towering gateway there, an obelisk taller than the last one, each ruler trying to out-build every predecessor and be remembered longer. Nobody ever declared it finished. It simply grew, until it became the largest religious building the world has ever seen.

To walk into it is to walk into two thousand years of ambition, competition and faith, all frozen in stone. And to walk into it at the right hour, with the right person, is to have most of it to yourself.

## The hall that stops people talking

You will have seen photographs of the Great Hypostyle Hall. They do not prepare you. A hundred and thirty-four stone columns, the tallest as wide as three people with arms outstretched, rise into what was once a roof — carved from base to capital, still holding their paint at the top where the sun couldn't bleach it. The scale is not describable at ground level; it has to be stood inside. People come in talking and go quiet.

Your Egyptologist does here what no guidebook can: reads the competition in the walls, shows you which king carved over which, and points to the two or three things worth the whole trip that ninety per cent of visitors walk straight past.

> Thirty pharaohs spent two thousand years trying to be the one you remember. Standing here, you remember all of them at once.

## Why the hour is everything

Karnak is vast, and by mid-morning it is full — coaches from the coast, forty-strong groups, flags in the air. But for roughly the first hour after the gates open, the great hall is nearly empty, the air is still cool, and the low sun throws long bars of gold between the columns. That hour is the entire difference between ticking off a monument and standing, quietly, inside the largest thing human beings built in the ancient world.

We know which gate opens first and how to time your arrival to catch it. Come early, come private, and let the greatest temple on earth belong to you for a while.
